{{Infobox officeholder | name = Jeromy Farkas | image = | imagesize = 150px | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada | residence = Calgary, Alberta | office = [[Calgary City Council|City of Calgary Councillor]] | constituency = Ward 11 | term_start = 2017 | term_end = | predecessor = Brian Pincott | successor = | religion = | alma_mater = University of Calgary | spouse = | occupation = | website = {{official|http://www.jeromy.ca}} | alma mater = }}
'''Jeromy Farkas''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who was elected to [[Calgary City Council]] in the [[Calgary municipal election, 2017|2017 municipal election]].<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/3840000/new-calgary-councillor-jeromy-farkas-turns-down-some-perks-of-the-job/ "New Calgary Councillor Jeromy Farkas turns down some perks of the job"]. [[Global News]], November 2, 2017.</ref> He represents Ward 11 on council, comprising the neighbourhoods of [[Acadia, Calgary|Acadia]], [[Bayview, Calgary|Bayview]], [[Bel-Aire, Calgary|Bel-Aire]], [[Braeside, Calgary|Braeside]], [[Britannia, Calgary|Britannia]], [[Cedarbrae, Calgary|Cedarbrae]], [[CFB Currie, Calgary|CFB Currie]], [[CFB Lincoln Park PMQ, Calgary|CFB Lincoln Park PMQ]], [[Chinook Park, Calgary|Chinook Park]], [[Eagle Ridge, Calgary|Eagle Ridge]], [[Elbow Park, Calgary|Elbow Park]] (part), [[Elboya, Calgary|Elboya]], [[Haysboro, Calgary|Haysboro]], [[Kelvin Grove, Calgary|Kelvin Grove]], [[Kingsland, Calgary|Kingsland]], [[Lakeview, Calgary|Lakeview]], [[Lincoln Park, Calgary|Lincoln Park,]] [[Mayfair, Calgary|Mayfair]], [[Meadowlark Park, Calgary|Meadowlark Park]], [[Mission, Calgary|Mission,]] [[North Glenmore Park, Calgary|North Glenmore Park,]] [[Oakridge, Calgary|Oakridge]], [[Palliser, Calgary|Palliser,]] [[Parkhill/Stanley Park, Calgary|Parkhill/Stanley Park]], [[Pump Hill, Calgary|Pump Hill]], [[Roxboro, Calgary|Rideau Park]], [[Roxboro, Calgary|Roxboro]], [[Rutland Park, Calgary|Rutland Park]], [[Southwood, Calgary|Southwood]], [[Willow Park, Calgary|Willow Park]] and [[Windsor Park, Calgary|Windsor Park]].
== Education == Farkas graduated from Calgary's [[Bishop Carroll High School (Calgary, Alberta)|Bishop Carroll High School]] and attended classes at the [[University of Calgary]] and received his bachelor of arts in political science and government.
== Manning Foundation == Prior to declaring his candidacy for Ward 11, Farkas worked as a senior fellow specializing in municipal governance at the [[Preston Manning|Manning Foundation]] for Democratic Education from February 2013 to January 2016. He was the project lead for the Council Tracker project, and published a report in September 2013 called "Growing the Democratic Toolbox: City Council Vote Tracking" where he studied City of Calgary Council meetings from fall 2010 to April 2013, specifically examining 73 votes during that period to understand how council worked, look at voting blocs, time spent in-camera (deliberations that are not open to the public), among other issues.<ref>http://www.metronews.ca/news/calgary/2014/05/28/see-how-calgary-councillors-vote-on-new-tracking-website-from-manning-foundation.html</ref><ref>https://www.scribd.com/document/169683010/Manning-Centre-Report-on-Calgary-City-Council</ref> He continued the project and established the website Counciltracker.com to track Calgary council activities, which he maintained until he left the Manning Foundation to run for Ward 11.
Farkas is a former ''[[Calgary Herald]]'' columnist writing about local issues, particularly city council, and contributed to ''Canadian Cycling'' magazine from 2015 to 2016.
== Provincial and federal politics == Formerly president of the [[Wildrose Party]]'s [[constituency association]] in [[Calgary-Elbow]],<ref name="lgbt">[http://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/local-wildrose-official-wants-party-to-become-champion-of-lgbtq-issues "Local Wildrose official wants party to become champion of LGBTQ issues"]. ''[[Calgary Herald]]'', June 3, 2016.</ref> Farkas identifies himself as a fiscal conservative and social liberal.<ref name="journal">[https://www.calgaryjournal.ca/index.php/city-hall/3461-jeromy-farkas-weighs-in-on-why-he-left-the-wildrose-constituency-to-run-for-calgary-city-council "Jeromy Farkas weighs in on why he left the Wildrose constituency to run for Calgary city council"]. ''Calgary Journal'', December 10, 2016.</ref> He describes his political views as being motivated by an attitude that "you should have the biggest say in how you live your life... chasing, again, the best solutions rather than the ones based in ideology," and has been active in issues such as wildlife conservation and human rights activism.<ref name="journal" /> He is out as [[bisexual]], becoming Calgary's first openly [[LGBTQ]] male city councillor,<ref>[http://www.metronews.ca/news/calgary/2017/10/18/the-power-and-pitfalls-of-a-diverse-council.html "The power and pitfalls of a diverse council"]. ''[[Metro International|Metro]]'', October 18, 2017.</ref> and played a key role in pushing the Wildrose Party to adopt a more progressive position on LGBTQ issues.<ref name="lgbt" />
== Calgary city council == His first significant act as a city councillor was to refuse several perks of the office, including councillors' [[pension]] plan and the transition allowance for new councillors.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jeromy-farkas-pension-declined-council-1.4384388 "Newly elected Calgary councillor turns down pension, transition allowance"]. [[CBC News]], November 2, 2017.</ref> He also vowed to oppose the city's new southwest [[List of Calgary Transit bus routes#BRT|bus rapid transit]] line.<ref>[http://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/ward-11-southwest-brt-divides-candidates "Ward 11: Jeromy Farkas vows to stop BRT in its tracks"]. ''[[Calgary Herald]]'', October 17, 2017.</ref>
In December 2017, his proposal for the city to provide additional compensation to residents of the Midfield [[trailer park]], which is being closed due to poor site design that makes it impossible for the city to repair the neighbourhood's failing water and sewer lines without tearing down the homes, failed to advance after Farkas was unable to find a councillor willing to [[second (parliamentary procedure)|second]] the motion.<ref>[https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/councillor-s-plans-for-midfield-mobile-home-park-falls-flat-1.3725839 "Councillor's plans for Midfield Mobile Home Park falls flat"]. [[CTV Calgary]], December 18, 2017.</ref>
In early 2018, he faced some criticism for being the sole councillor to vote against a motion directing city staff to draft a new [[parental leave]] policy for city councillors, on the grounds that taking time away from city council business would be a betrayal of the constituents.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4048956/calgary-councillor-criticized-parental-leave-policy/ "Calgary councillor criticized for suggesting parental leave would be ‘betrayal’ of constituents"]. [[Global Calgary]], February 26, 2018.</ref>
